    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Could it also be related to the interlacement pattern itself? I'm worried that if the weave isn't tight enough or if the structure is too loose in some spots, it's going to compromise the integrity of the fabric. We need these to be a solid, impenetrable barrier for our premium line to ensure nothing gets through the fibers.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, the interlacement pattern is absolutely critical, and if it's not tight enough, it will definitely compromise the fabric's integrity. A loose weave, even with high yarn counts, will have weak points, which is exactly what you don't want for a premium barrier. It's like trying to build a wall with loose stones; the whole structure is vulnerable to any small push.\n\nThe pattern itself dictates the strength. If the shed formation—the opening created by the warp and weft—is uneven, or if the insertion of the weft yarn isn't perfectly aligned with the warp threads, you get those gaps you're seeing. A sloppy interlacement is a recipe for failure, making the fabric porous instead of impenetrable.",
      "source": "target",
